{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"CSS Syntax","slug":"css-syntax","subject":"CSS","category":"Web Development","level":"Beginner","estimated_read_time":"10 mins","prerequisites":["CSS Introduction"],"learning_objectives":["Understand the structure of a CSS rule-set","Learn about selectors, properties, and values","Understand the role of curly braces and semicolons"],"theory":"A CSS rule-set consists of a selector and a declaration block.\n\nThe **selector** points to the HTML element you want to style.\n\nThe **declaration block** contains one or more declarations separated by semicolons.\n\nEach declaration includes a **CSS property name** and a **value**, separated by a colon.\n\nA CSS declaration always ends with a semicolon, and declaration blocks are surrounded by curly braces.","syntax":"selector {\n  property: value;\n  property: value;\n}","examples":[{"code":"p {\n  color: red;\n  text-align: center;\n}","output":"All <p> elements will be red and center-aligned.","explanation":"`p` is the selector. `color` is a property, and `red` is the property value. `text-align` is another property with `center` as its value."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Forgetting the semicolon","correction":"Always end each declaration with a semicolon (;).","example":"WRONG:\np {\n  color: red\n  text-align: center\n}\n\nCORRECT:\np {\n  color: red;\n  text-align: center;\n}"},{"mistake":"Using equals sign instead of colon","correction":"Use a colon (:) to separate property and value, not an equals sign (=).","example":"WRONG: color = red;\nCORRECT: color: red;"}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"What are the three parts of a CSS syntax?","answer":"A selector, a property, and a value.","difficulty":"Easy"}],"practice_problems":[{"problem":"Fix the syntax error in this CSS rule: `h1 { color red; }`","hint":"Look at the separator between the property and value.","solution":"h1 { color: red; }","difficulty":"Easy"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Style Sheets Maintenance"